SPORTS; With Words to Spare, Schenkel Strikes a Chord}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Miller (sports announcer)|Bob Miller]] (1993\u20131994)\n* [[Sam Rosen (sportscaster)|Sam Rosen]] (1993\u20131994)<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC set to drop puck for Bruins-Caps|author=Jim Baker|newspaper=Boston Herald|page=B20|date=March 27, 1994}}</ref>\n* [[Dave Strader]] (1999\u20132002)\n* [[Gary Thorne]] (1993\u20131994, 1999\u20132004)<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports on the Air NHL not bouncing like NBA|author=Jim Baker|newspaper=[[Boston Herald]]|page=B18|date=May 9, 1993}}</ref>\n\n===Color commentators===\n* [[Bill Clement]] (1993\u20131994, 1999\u20132004)\n* [[John Davidson (ice hockey)|John Davidson]] (1993\u20131994, 2002\u20132004)\n* [[Brian Engblom]] (2002\u20132004)\n* [[Barry Melrose]] (1999\u20132002)\n* [[Darren Pang]] (1993\u20131994, 1999\u20132004)\n* [[Jim Schoenfeld]] (1993\u20131994)\n\n===Reporters===\n* [[Brenda Brenon]] (1993\u20131994)<ref>{{cite news|title=BRENON KNOWS HER HOCKEY ABC'S|newspaper=[[The Buffalo News]]|date=April 17, 1994}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Jones (sportscaster)|Mark Jones]] (1993\u20131994)\n* [[Tom Mees]] (1993\u20131994)\n* [[Al Morganti]] (1993\u20131994)\n* [[Bob Neumeier]] (1993\u20131994)\n\n==Nielsen ratings==\n{{Main article|Ratings for The NHL on ABC}}\n\n==National Hockey League coverage on ABC owned-and-operated television stations==\n{{main article|ABC Owned Television Stations|Owned-and-operated television stations in the United States|Historical NHL over-the-air television broadcasters}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|'''Team'''\n|'''Stations'''\n|'''Years'''\n|-\n|[[Philadelphia Flyers]]\n|[[WPVI-TV]] 6\n|[[1983\u201384 Philadelphia Flyers season|1983]]&ndash;[[1985\u201386 Philadelphia Flyers season|1986]]\n|-\n|[[San Jose Sharks]]\n|[[KGO-TV]] 7\n|[[1991\u201392 San Jose Sharks season|1991]]&ndash;[[1993\u201394 San Jose Sharks season|1994]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<div style=\"font-size: 85%\">\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040815194650/http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/abcsports/television |date=15 August 2004 |title=Official site }}\n* [http://www.jsonline.com/sports/etc/ap/jul01/ap-hkn-nhl-tv-chan071101.asp NHL, ESPN-ABC Seek Viewers]\n*[http://www.sportsmediawatch.net/2007/05/how-disney-outfoxed-nhl.html Sports Media Watch: How Disney outfoxed the NHL.]\n</div>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before=[[NHL on NBC|NBC]]| title=NHL network broadcast partner<br> (with [[NHL on NBC|NBC]]) in the United States| years=[[1992\u201393 NHL season|1992]] \u2013 [[1993\u201394 NHL season|1994]]| after=[[NHL on Fox|Fox]]}}\n{{succession box|before=[[NHL on Fox|Fox]]| title=NHL network broadcast partner<br> in the United States| years=[[1999\u20132000 NHL season|2000]] \u2013 [[2003\u201304 NHL season|2004]]| after=[[NHL on NBC|NBC]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{National Hockey League on national television}}\n{{NHL on ABC}}\n{{ESPN National Hockey Night}}\n{{ESPN on ABC}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nhl on ABC,The}}\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American television series]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:ABC Sports]]\n[[Category:ABC Radio Networks]]\n[[Category:ABC Radio Sports]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League on television|ABC]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League on the radio|ABC]]\n[[Category:1993 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1994 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2004 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Television series}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=September 2014}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = NHL on ABC\n| image                = Nhlonabc.jpg\n| caption              = ''NHL on ABC'' logo used from 1999 to 2004\n| show_name_2          = \n| genre                = [[Hockey|Hockey telecasts]]\n| creator              = \n| director             = \n| presenter            = [[John Saunders (journalist)|John Saunders]]<br>[[Gary Thorne]]<br>[[Mike Emrick]]<br>[[Al Michaels]]<br>[[Bill Clement]]<br>[[Jim Schoenfeld]]<br>[[John Davidson (hockey player)|John Davidson]]<br>[[Al Morganti]]<br>[[Barry Melrose]]<br> [[Chris Berman]]<br>[[Steve Levy]]<br>[[Dave Strader]]<br>[[Darren Pang]]<br>[[Brian Engblom]]<br>[[Erin Andrews]]<br>[[Sam Ryan]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = Bob Christianson\n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 2 ([[1992\u201393 NHL season|1992]]&ndash;[[1993\u201394 NHL season|94]] version)<br>5 ([[1999\u20132000 NHL season|1999]]&ndash;[[2003\u201304 NHL season|2004]] version)<br>7 (total)\n| num_episodes         = \n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = \n| producer             = \n| editor               = \n| location             = [[List of National Hockey League stadiums|Various NHL stadiums]] {{small|(game telecasts)}}\n| cinematography       = \n| camera               = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 180 minutes or until end of game\n| company              = [[ESPN on ABC|ABC Sports]]<br>[[ESPN]]\n| distributor          = \n| network              = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| picture_format       = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]),<br>[[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]])\n| first_aired          = {{Plainlist|\n*'''First run:''' {{Start date|1993|3|28}}\u2013{{End date|1994|5|1}}\n*'''Second run:''' {{Start date|2000|2|6}} \n}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2004|6|7}}\n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = ''[[NHL on NBC]]''\n| related              = ''[[ESPN National Hockey Night]]''\n| website              = https://abcnews.go.com/search?searchtext=NHL\n| production_website   = \n}}\n\nThe '''''NHL on ABC''''' is the branding formerly used for broadcasts of [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) games televised on the [[American Broadcasting Company]] (ABC) in the United States. The network first broadcast NHL games during the [[1992\u201393 NHL season|1992\u201393 season]] under a [[brokered programming|time-buy agreement]] with [[ESPN]]; ABC resumed regular season game telecasts on February 6, [[1999\u20132000 NHL season|2000]], as part of a joint contract with ESPN that also gave ABC the rights to select games from each round of the [[Stanley Cup playoffs]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Before the 1992\u201393 NHL season===\nAfter being dropped by [[NHL on NBC|NBC]] after the {{NHL Year|1974}} season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey, Violence and Movies|author=Frederick C. Klein|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=March 25, 1977}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sports check on what's new|author=Ross Atkin|newspaper=[[Christian Science Monitor]]|page=19|date=June 9, 1975}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=5 New Coaches Will Try to Dethrone the Flyers|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=D8|date=October 8, 1975}}</ref> the NHL did not maintain a national television contract in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey in battle for TV life!|author=George Langford|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=I3|date=October 5, 1975}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Problems of Overexpansion Continue to Haunt NBA and NHL|author=[[Joe Durso|Joseph Durso]]|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|page=A16|date=July 13, 1977}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NHL's President-Elect Scores Points With His Take-Charge Attitude|author=Robin Herman|newspaper=The New York Times|page=24|date=June 28, 1977}}</ref> In response to this, the league put together a [[The NHL Network (1975\u201379)|network]] of [[independent station (North America)|independent stations]] covering approximately 55% of the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=Holiday TV Hurts Series|newspaper=The New York Times|page=137|date=December 28, 1975}}</ref><ref name=NewYork>{{cite news|title=NHL Plans Cup TV; Seeks New York Outlet|newspaper=The New York Times|page=46|date=March 23, 1976}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey needs TV blanket to keep it warm in U.S.|author=Bob Verdi|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=E1|date=January 17, 1979}}</ref>\n\nGames typically aired on Monday nights<ref name=Chicago>{{cite news|title=TV hockey back, but no Hawks|author=Gary Deeb|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|page=C2|date=November 9, 1976}}</ref> (beginning at 8 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]]) or Saturday afternoons. The package was offered to local stations without a rights fee.<ref>{{cite news|title=SHRINKING ACT|author=Gary Deeb|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|page=E4|date=February 23, 1979}}</ref> Profits would instead be derived from the advertising, which was about evenly split between the network and the local station. The Monday night games were often billed as \"''The NHL Game of the Week''\".<ref>{{cite news|title=NHL Starts Tonight: Action but No TV|author=Don Merry|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=E2|date=October 11, 1978}}</ref>\n\nInitially, the Monday night package was marketed to [[List of ABC television affiliates (by U.S. state)|ABC affiliates]]; the idea being that ABC carried [[Monday Night Football|NFL football games on Monday nights]] in the fall and (starting in May {{baseball year|1976}}) [[Monday Night Baseball|Major League Baseball games on Monday nights]] in the spring and summer, stations would want the hockey telecasts to create a year-round Monday night sports block; however, very few ABC stations chose to pick up the package.\n\nIn {{NHL Year|1978|end}}, ABC was contracted to televise Game 7 of the [[1979 Stanley Cup Finals|Stanley Cup Finals]].<ref>{{cite news|title=May 26 Selected For a 7th Game|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|page=S4|date=May 13, 1979}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NHL, ABC-TV Agree|agency=[[Associated Press]]|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|page=89|date=May 13, 1979}}</ref> Since the Finals ended in five games, the contract was void.<ref>{{cite news|title=Montreal win kills ABC TV deal but Ziegler feels pact is on way|author=Donald Ramsay|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]|page=P35|date=May 22, 1979}}</ref>\n\nIt was also around this time that ABC offered the NHL a limited deal that [[NHL commissioner|NHL president]] [[John Ziegler Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://puckjunk.com/2018/10/29/john-ziegler-did-more-harm-than-good-for-hockey/|title=John Ziegler Did More Harm Than Good for Hockey|last=Barry|first=Sal|date=October 29, 2018|website=Punk Junk|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> quickly rejected. ABC wanted to split the network and show the NHL in the [[Northeastern United States|Northeast]] and [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]] and [[NASCAR on ESPN|NASCAR]] in the [[Southern United States|South]] on Sunday afternoons.\n\n====ABC's coverage of the Winter Olympics====\nIt should be noted that even though ABC didn't yet televise National Hockey League games, they were the [[ABC Olympic broadcasts|American network broadcast home]] of the [[Winter Olympics|Winter Olympic]] games beginning in [[1964 Winter Olympics|1964]] and continuing through the [[1988 Winter Olympics|1988 Winter Games]] from [[Calgary]]. For the [[Ice hockey at the Olympic Games|ice hockey events]], employed [[Curt Gowdy]] for play-by-play [[Olympics on ABC commentators|duties]] in [[Ice hockey at the 1968 Winter Olympics|1968]] and [[Ice hockey at the 1976 Winter Olympics|1976]] ([[NBC Olympic broadcasts|NBC]] had the broadcasting rights for the [[1972 Winter Olympics|1972 Games]] in the interim) Games. Gowdy worked with [[Brian Conacher]] for the 1976 ice hockey events.\n\nFor years [[Ice hockey at the 1980 Winter Olympics|later]] at [[Lake Placid, New York|Lake Placid]], ABC was on hand for a medal-round men's [[ice hockey]] game that would soon become known the \"[[Miracle on Ice]]\". On February 22, 1980, the [[United States men's national ice hockey team|United States]] team, made up of [[amateur]] and [[college sports|collegiate]] players and led by coach [[Herb Brooks]], defeated the [[Soviet Union national ice hockey team|Soviet team]], which consisted of veteran professional players with significant experience in international play. The rest of the United States (except those who watched the game live on Canadian television) had to wait to see the game, as ABC decided to broadcast the late-afternoon game on tape delay in prime time.<ref name=espn>[http://espn.go.com/classic/s/miracle_ice_1980.html \"College kids perform Olympic miracle\"], ESPN.com</ref> Sportscaster [[Al Michaels]], who was calling the game on ABC along with former [[Montreal Canadiens]] goalie [[Ken Dryden]], picked up on the countdown in his broadcast, and delivered his famous call:<ref name=youtube2>{{YouTube|id=QTev5pSuYLk|title=1980 Miracle On Ice}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Eleven seconds, you've got ten seconds, the countdown going on right now! [[Ken Morrow|Morrow]], up to [[Dave Silk|Silk]]. Five seconds left in the game. Do you believe in miracles? YES!}}\n\nAl Michaels would continue serving as ABC's top play-by-play announcer for their ice hockey coverage for their next two Winter Olympics. In [[Ice hockey at the 1984 Winter Olympics|1984]] from [[Sarajevo]], Michaels again worked alongside Ken Dryden while [[Mike Eruzione]], who was the [[Captain (ice hockey)|captain]], of the gold medal winning United States ice hockey team from 1980, primarily worked with [[Don Chevrier]]. For ABC's final Winter Olympics [[Ice hockey at the 1988 Winter Olympics|four years later]], Michaels was once again, working with Dryden while Eruzione was this time, paired with [[Jiggs McDonald]].\n\n====ABC Radio coverage (1989\u20131991)====\nIn 1989,<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC RADIO GETS STANLEY CUP|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|date=September 12, 1989}}</ref> the NHL signed a two-year contract (lasting through the {{NHL Year|1990}} season) with [[Citadel Media|ABC Radio]] for the broadcast rights to the All-Star Game and Stanley Cup Finals.<ref>{{cite news|title=NOTEBOOK; Regular Season Honors to Bruins; Liut Top Goalie|author=Robert Fachet|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|page=B08|date=April 3, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=TV deal offers another chance but CFL needs a career year|author=Rob Grant|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|page=C.8|date=May 17, 1991}}</ref> ABC Radio named [[Don Chevrier]] and [[Phil Esposito]] as their main commentating crew.<ref>{{cite news|title=Relief role McGwire's dream|author=Milt Dunnell|newspaper=Toronto Star|page=G1|date=July 16, 1989}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Munchies List is Some Food for Thought|newspaper=[[Worcester Telegram & Gazette]]|page=B8|date=May 19, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cool Goodyear feels the heat of Indy-scribable media hype|author=Rob Grant|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=May 19, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Palmer heads the short list as replacement for Kubek|author=Ken McKee|newspaper=Toronto Star|page=B7|date=December 22, 1989}}</ref>\n\n===Time-buy deal with ESPN (1992\u20131994)===\nIn the {{NHL Year|1992}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Network Lineup|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1138127/index.htm|author=Steve Wulf|journal=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=December 27, 1993}}</ref> and {{NHL Year|1993}} seasons, ABC televised six<ref>{{cite news |last=|first=|date=September 2, 1992|title=NHL strikes TV deal with ESPN|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1992/09/02/NHL-strikes-TV-deal-with-ESPN/2438715406400/|work=UPI|location= |access-date= }}</ref> weekly regional telecasts<ref>{{cite news|title=NHL governors \"ecstatic' over reported TV package|newspaper=[[Kitchener-Waterloo Record]]|page=E2|date=August 27, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Hot Not|url=http://cnnsi.printthis.clickability.com/pt/cpt?action=cpt&title=While+the+NBA%27s+image+has+cooled%2C+the+NHL+has+ignited+-+06.20.94+-+SI+Vault&expire=&urlID=421025542&fb=Y&url=http%3A%2F%2Fsportsillustrated.cnn.com%2Fvault%2Farticle%2Fmagazine%2FMAG1005307%2F4%2Findex.htm&partnerID=289881|author=E.M. Swift|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=June 20, 1994}}</ref> on Sunday afternoons beginning in March<ref>{{cite news|title=NHL's new boss ready to clear up confusion|author=Rudy Martzke|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|page=3C|date=February 5, 1993}}</ref> (or the last three Sundays<ref>{{cite news|title=Camera could be newest Derby rider|author=Michael Hiestand|newspaper=USA Today|page=3C|date=April 28, 1993}}</ref> of the regular season). This marked the first time that regular season National Hockey League games were broadcast on American network television<ref>{{cite news|title=Select few watching NHL on ABC|author=Jim Shea|newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]]|page=E9|date=May 7, 1993}}</ref> since {{NHL Year|1974}} (when [[NBC]] was the NHL's American broadcast television partner). ABC would then televise three weeks worth of playoff games<ref>{{cite news|title=Weighty ESPY awards get lighthearted touch|author=Michael Heistand|newspaper=USA Today|page=3C|date=March 4, 1993}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NHL BOSS FINISHES EVENTFUL 1ST YEAR BETTMAN FOCUSES ON CBS DEAL|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|author=Mike Kiley|page=3|date=January 21, 1994}}</ref> (or the first three Sundays<ref>{{cite news|title=NBC WINS WITH LOTTERY, EAST FINALS|author=Jorge Milan|newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel|Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel]]|page=7C|date=May 22, 1993}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=TV picture still fuzzy for NHL playoff schedule|author=Ken McKee|newspaper=Toronto Star|page=E8|date=April 15, 1994}}</ref> of the playoffs<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC to help showcase NHL with 5 playoff games|author=Randy Covitz|newspaper=[[Kansas City Star]]|page=D6|date=March 6, 1993}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=He's Muni-ficent: Oilers coach lavishes praise on new Hawk|author=Mike Kiley|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|page=12|date=March 28, 1993}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=HOCKEY; N.H.L. Is About to Showcase Lemieux and the Prime-Time Penguins|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/11/sports/hockey-nhl-is-about-to-showcase-lemieux-and-the-prime-time-penguins.html?pagewanted=print|author=Joe LaPointe|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 11, 1993}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hawks must win Norris to make ABC telecast|author=Mike Kiley|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|page=11|date=April 12, 1993}}</ref>). The network did not televise the [[Stanley Cup Finals]], which instead, were televised nationally by [[ESPN National Hockey Night|ESPN]] and by [[Fox Sports West and Prime Ticket|Prime Ticket]] in [[1992\u201393 Los Angeles Kings season|Los Angeles]] ({{scfy|1993}}) and [[MSG (TV network)|MSG Network]] in [[1993\u201394 New York Rangers season|New York]] ({{scfy|1994}}). Games televised on ABC were not subject to [[Blackout (broadcasting)|blackout]].\n\nThese broadcasts (just as was the case with the [[1999\u20132000 NHL season|1999]]\u2013[[2003\u201304 NHL season|2004]] package) were essentially, [[Brokered programming|time-buys]]<ref>{{cite news|title=NHL announces TV deal but some details murky|date=September 3, 1992|author=Michael Hiestand|newspaper=USA Today|page=3C}}</ref> by ESPN.<ref>{{cite news|title=TOO MUCH PUNCH RUINS NHL PARTY|author=Craig Davis|newspaper=Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel|page=1C|date=August 22, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fox makes hockey its newest surprise|author=Rudy Martzke|newspaper=USA Today|page=3C|date=September 12, 1994}}</ref> In other words, ABC would sell three-hour blocks of airtime to ESPN<ref>{{cite news |last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=August 27, 1992|title=HOCKEY; Legal Sabers Rattle Over N.H.L. TV Plan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/27/sports/hockey-legal-sabers-rattle-over-nhl-tv-plan.html|work=New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref>, which in return, would produce, supply broadcasters and sell advertising. Also as evidence by ABC's [[Raycom Media|Raycom]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Sports4 |url=http://www.onlinesports.com/sportstrust/sports4.html |work=Online Sports |quote=The biggest time-buy arrangement is between Raycom and ABC. For the 1991\u201392 season, it paid ABC $1.8 million for six weeks of air time\u201413 telecasts\u2014covering 26 college basketball games regionally. Raycom used ABC on-air talent including Brent Musburger, Dick Vitale, Jim Valvano, Gary Bender, Cheryl Miller, and Mark Jones. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928060946/http://www.onlinesports.com/sportstrust/sports4.html |archivedate=September 28, 2011 }}</ref> produced [[ESPN College Basketball on ABC|college basketball package]] around the same time period, this arrangement could also be interpreted as a way to avoid union contracts, which require that 100[[Percentage|%]] of network shows had to use crew staff who were network union members.<ref>{{cite web|title=It's Bottom-line Time|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1066553/3/index.htm|author=William Taaffe|work=Sports Illustrated|publisher=Time Inc.|date=October 12, 1987|quote=Also revealing is ABC's whirlwind use of network crews on last season's college basketball games. The cameramen and technicians typically arrived at an arena to set up at around 2:00&nbsp;a.m. on the day of the game so the network could save on expenses. They then caught a few hours' sleep, returned to the arena to televise the game, broke down the equipment and flew home so as not to run up costs the following day.}}</ref> The main difference is that the graphics used for the telecasts were those used by ABC Sports, instead of the ones seen on ''[[ESPN National Hockey Night]]''. In later years, the roles would be reversed as ESPN's graphical style would be used on the broadcasts with the exception of intermission reports. ABC even used ESPN's theme music<ref>{{YouTube|title=NHL on ESPN Theme |id=8PReim0Axt4}}</ref> (composed by Bob Christianson) for the 1992\u20131994 coverage. During ABC's next stint with the NHL, the network used its own theme music.<ref>{{YouTube|title=NHL on ABC full theme|id=wnE5K5ofG5c}}</ref>\n\nOverall, ABC averaged a 1.7 [[Nielsen ratings|rating]]<ref>{{cite book|title=International sports law and business, Volume 3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TGgjAAAAMAAJ&q=National+Hockey+League+on+USA+Network&dq=National+Hockey+League+on+USA+Network&hl=en&ei=_D9HTaLZFoKmsQPr2MCpAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CGwQ6AEwCQ|author=Aaron N. Wise and Bruce S. Meyer|publisher=Kluwer Law International|isbn=|page=1704|year=1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=DiGivanna|first=Mike|date=October 3, 1993|title=MIGHTY DUCKS '93-94: PREMIERE SEASON : A Brave new NHL : As It Welcomes Two New Members, the National Hockey League Ponders What It Needs to Do to Become the Sport of the '90s|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-10-03/news/ss-42587_1_national-hockey-league|work=Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Coach`s Corner - ABC covering the NHL|id=WiVK2JnPbjE}}</ref> for those two seasons. [[John Saunders (journalist)|John Saunders]] was the studio pregame/intermission anchor just like he would be for the 1999-2004 NHL package on ABC.\n\nWhen the NHL television contract went up for negotiation in early 1994, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] (which was in the process of launching its [[Fox Sports (United States)|sports division]] after acquiring the rights to the [[National Football Conference]] of the [[National Football League|NFL]]) and [[CBS]] (which was hoping to land a major sports contract to replace the [[NFL on CBS|NFL]] rights that they lost to [[NFL on Fox|Fox]] and [[Major League Baseball on CBS|Major League Baseball]] rights that they lost to [[The Baseball Network|ABC and NBC]]) competed heavily for the package. On September 9, 1994, the National Hockey League reached a five-year, US$155 million contract with [[NHL on Fox|Fox]] for the broadcast television rights to the league's games, beginning with the [[1994\u201395 NHL season|1994\u201395 season]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Fox Outbids CBS for N.H.L. Games|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9403E2DD163BF933A2575AC0A962958260&scp=4&sq=National+Hockey+League+Fox&st=nyt|author=Richard Sandomir|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 10, 1994|accessdate=March 20, 2008}}</ref> effectively ending ABC's time-buy deal with ESPN after just two seasons.\n\n====Schedules====\n\n=====1993\u201394=====\n{{Main article|1993\u201394 NHL season}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Date\n! Teams\n! Start times (All times Eastern)\n|-\n|March 27<ref>{{cite news|title=NO MORE LIFE IN A FISHBOWL|date=March 24, 1994|author=Jerry Lindquist|newspaper=Richmond Times-Dispatch|page=C4}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PRESIDENTIAL PRIORITIES: CLINTON CUTS OFF FOR GAME|date=March 25, 1994|author=Dan Caesar|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|page=4G}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NATIONAL AUDIENCE IS AGAIN ABOUT TO GET ABCS OF HOCKEY|date=March 25, 1994|author=Dan Caesar|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|page=5G}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Reality Check for Iafrate, Juneau; Traded Players Meet for First Time Today as Capitals Host Bruins|date=March 27, 1994|author=Dave Sell|newspaper=The Washington Post|page=D07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Capitals Doing It Hard Way; Try to Beat Stars For Third Straight|date=April 3, 1994|author=Dave Sell|newspaper=The Washington Postt|page=D10}}</ref>\n|[[1993\u201394 Boston Bruins season|Boston]] at [[1993\u201394 Washington Capitals season|Washington]]<br>[[Blackhawks\u2013Red Wings rivalry|Detroit at Chicago]]<br>[[1993\u201394 New York Rangers season|New York Rangers]] at [[1993\u201394 Winnipeg Jets season|Winnipeg]]<br>[[1993\u201394 Los Angeles Kings season|Los Angeles]] at [[1993\u201394 Vancouver Canucks season|Vancouv